  <static seed="1258" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/addSubtractRationalExpressions70.pg">
    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{1}{y+3}+\frac{6}{y^{2}-9}} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{1}{y-3}, y\ne -3</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{1}{y+3}+\frac{6}{y^{2}-9}} 
      \amp = {\frac{1}{y+3}}+\frac{6}{(y+3)(y-3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{1\cdot({y-3})}{({y+3})\cdot({y-3})} +\frac{6}{(y+3)(y-3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{{y-3+6}}{(y+3)(y-3)} \\
      \amp = \frac{{y+3}}{(y+3)(y-3)} \\
      \amp = {\frac{1}{y-3}, y\ne -3}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>{y+3}</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>y \ne {-3}</m>.</p>
</solution>
